<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/121571516-pralay-dakua"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/121571516-pralay-dakua">Pralay Dakua</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Does longer stay in a place provides more accuracy of events? I am not sure. We all live in our own bubbles - just like two sisters of &quot;Mon Amie&quot;, or <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Does longer stay in a place provides more accuracy of events? I am not sure. We all live in our own bubbles - just like two sisters of "Mon Amie", or the lonely retired judge with his dog and cook. We look at anything else outside of own bubbles with a perspective of "stereotype". That way, stereotypes are relevant parts of narrative. The author provides a multi-faceted narrative, a very strong one, of post-colonial time and mindset. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
