    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3399605545" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3399605545" />
    <a title="Edgarr Alien Pooh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111745799-edgarr-alien-pooh"><img alt="Edgarr Alien Pooh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1585112748p2/111745799.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3399605545?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edgarr Alien Pooh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edgarr Alien Pooh" href="/user/show/111745799-edgarr-alien-pooh">Edgarr Alien Pooh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780241143643" href="/book/show/2426918.The_Inheritance_of_Loss">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111745799-edgarr-alien-pooh?shelf=general-fiction">general-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3399605545" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11921880845581777123">Desai&apos;s Inheritance of Loss is about the changing face of India as it struggled to find it&apos;s legitimate place. A country that was proudly a united one, now mixed with Muslims, Hindus, Shieks, Nepalese and Tibetans. Added to the pot are some British colonials hanging on and an influx of tourists who view the country as that of a third world nation.<br/>But India is proud of its heritage, generations have grown up with poverty and poor conditions, but families have stood strong, united, and predominant</span>
  <span id="freeText11921880845581777123" style="display:none">Desai's Inheritance of Loss is about the changing face of India as it struggled to find it's legitimate place. A country that was proudly a united one, now mixed with Muslims, Hindus, Shieks, Nepalese and Tibetans. Added to the pot are some British colonials hanging on and an influx of tourists who view the country as that of a third world nation.<br />But India is proud of its heritage, generations have grown up with poverty and poor conditions, but families have stood strong, united, and predominantly happy. But these are changing times, the new generations are flying to England for sophisticated educations or traveling to the U.S to find riches in better employment. The colonials still feel like it is their land and the locals are there to serve them as cooks, gardeners, and the like.<br />Those left behind strive to continue their way of life but there are uprisings amongst the people, send the Muslims to Pakistan, the Nepalese back to Nepal and Tibetans home to Tibet they say. This is the time of Indira Gandhi's assassination, at the age of 66.<br />The story takes place in Kalimpong, a region of India wedged between Bhutan, Nepal, and Bangladesh to its South.<br /><br />The Inheritance of Loss continued my sketchy relationship with major literary award winners, this having won both the Booker Prize and the National Book Critics Circle award for fiction. It is not that it is an uninteresting read, far from it and the last quarter of the book really picked up but for me it was "over" written. I found the first half of the book to jump around too much to get to really invest in the characters and everything attracted a full glossary of adjectives - be it a small plant in a pot or large house. This made it a bit hard to keep track of family relationships and those who were friends in the township.<br />I guess to that aspect I was a little disappointed because I wanted to really rip through this like I did with Kite Runner and Shadow of the Wind, and experience a world that is foreign to me but I found myself concentrating more on who was who rather than the overall story.<br />A three star rating as it wasn't really for me but is far from a write off. I can see that many people would really enjoy this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11921880845581777123" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


