<div id="review_1297180983" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1297180983" />
    <a title="Vonia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5204784-vonia"><img alt="Vonia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610826126p2/5204784.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1297180983?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vonia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vonia" href="/user/show/5204784-vonia">Vonia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=war">war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=india">india</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=political">political</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=orphans">orphans</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=man-booker-prize">man-booker-prize</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=location-as-character">location-as-character</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=law">law</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=dysfunctional-families">dysfunctional-families</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=romance">romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1297180983" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9640663334618411477">Truth be told, I feel like I hated this novel. Alas, I realize that I am being unduly biased against it for a few reasons. The primary reason is how lauded it is, including winning an award that I have a special respect for: The Man Booker Prize (2006). This is thus far the most undeserving winner that I have read. <br/><br/>To begin with, this novel has no focus; it has some colorful characters, some touching scenes, some inspiring vignettes, an overall well researched amount of data regarding immigratio</span>
  <span id="freeText9640663334618411477" style="display:none">Truth be told, I feel like I hated this novel. Alas, I realize that I am being unduly biased against it for a few reasons. The primary reason is how lauded it is, including winning an award that I have a special respect for: The Man Booker Prize (2006). This is thus far the most undeserving winner that I have read. <br /><br />To begin with, this novel has no focus; it has some colorful characters, some touching scenes, some inspiring vignettes, an overall well researched amount of data regarding immigration, urbanization, colonization, modernization. On this, Desai does indeed deliver. But, placed together, they are like pieces of a puzzle with most of the box missing. <br /><br />The characters in a story can make up for a lot. Unfortunately, I found myself unable to connect with, empathize with, see nor feel alongside any. Even Sai, the vivacious, admirable young heroine, was exactly that. A character I could admire for her wit and courage. But that was all. <br /><br />Her romance with Gyan I really could never understand; mostly, I found it rather dull and two dimensional, almost unconvincing. The cook, unnamed until the last two pages, was a colorful character whom I felt an affinity for; at times, I felt like I knew him, but barely. His son Biju, was immersed in the panoply of faces that is New York City and although we were told his story, he was really simply another blank face. Sai's grandfather was the worst. I found his past abuse of his wife, his insistence on being a %*+= to everyone within contact, rarely even showing love to those closest to him, inexcusable. He may have had some difficulties in his past, but nothing that excuses him today. Predictably, the only person, thing, being, he will be seen loving is Mutt. I suppose it makes sense, then, that Mutt serves as a sort of voiceless wheel necessary for the climax in the ending of the novel. His role is redemption for the story? For the characters? Merely more evidence of what can go wrong in society? <br /><br />From what I know in history, her documentation of India's slow, reluctant modernization seems accurate, as does this country's ridiculousness of immigration laws, the difficulties inherent in fooling the system for a Green Card (it is not even green!), the concotion of cultures, heritages, traditions, cuisines that iconizes New York City. <br /><br />There is also a decent amount of humour to be found throughout the novel, which is always appreciated when such serious themes are being adressed. Several difficult topics are covered throughout the course of the novel, including the wars, the genocide, the gangs. The intimidation endured by various individuals in the course of the novel; emotional and physical, psychological and physiological turmoil experienced in various dimensions. It is all expressed well. Poetically on the one hand, but somehow the execution falls short. One realizes this only when reading the story as a whole. Problems x, y, z; a through z are adressed, presented, explored, extricated. Then what? Then nothing. It is as if the author is making a statement to the effect, "Here are all the problems, all the problems with no solutions. The End." As a short story, even several short stories, The Inheritance Of Loss would have fared far better.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9640663334618411477" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


