    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2200792744" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2200792744" />
    <a title="Fiona" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8641338-fiona"><img alt="Fiona" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611901771p2/8641338.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2200792744?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fiona" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fiona" href="/user/show/8641338-fiona">Fiona</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141027289" href="/book/show/561571.The_Inheritance_of_Loss">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8641338-fiona?shelf=general-fiction">general-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2200792744" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14471227031378528980">I’d like to thank the person who bought this book in Waverley Station, Edinburgh on 2/11/09, probably to read on a train journey, and subsequently left it for me to find in a charity shop on the outskirts of Glasgow. I bought it because I liked the title and the cover, a method I’ve found quite reliable in finding good books and new authors, serendipitous though it is!<br/><br/>This is one of the best books I’ve read in a long time. It deservedly won the Man Booker in 2006. It is set in the years of the c</span>
  <span id="freeText14471227031378528980" style="display:none">I’d like to thank the person who bought this book in Waverley Station, Edinburgh on 2/11/09, probably to read on a train journey, and subsequently left it for me to find in a charity shop on the outskirts of Glasgow. I bought it because I liked the title and the cover, a method I’ve found quite reliable in finding good books and new authors, serendipitous though it is!<br /><br />This is one of the best books I’ve read in a long time. It deservedly won the Man Booker in 2006. It is set in the years of the conflict over Gorkhaland, in India, and concentrates on just a few main characters. We join them in their thoughts and personal turmoil about their past, their present and the future. None of them are easy to like but all are written about with compassion and a depth of understanding that is sometimes prosaic, sometimes profound. The inevitable atrocities and their effects on the main characters and general population are related in such a matter of fact way that the tragedy of it all is felt so much more.<br /><br />There is a lot of humour in this book. Desai gently ridicules the aspirations of those whose goal is to make it big in America or to uphold their version of a middle class English lifestyle in Northern India. Halfway through, I knew I would read this book again. Quite simply, it’s wonderfully written and I can’t recommend it highly enough.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14471227031378528980" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

