  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/869800857" />
    <a title="Doug" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25667717-doug"><img alt="Doug" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1605117426p2/25667717.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/869800857?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Doug" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Doug" href="/user/show/25667717-doug">Doug</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143101222" href="/book/show/561573.The_Inheritance_Of_Loss">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer869800857" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3466271165077877555">Although much of Desai&apos;s writing is lovely and lyrical, the lack of narrative drive (or to be honest, anything remotely resembling a plot) made this a bit of a drag. Others have mentioned the humor, but I found the entire thing almost relentlessly depressing, despite the quirky characters. I found the ending chapters (which includes the kidnapping of a beloved animal, something that I found both a pandering to the emotions - and ultimately heartbreaking), disturbingly unsatisfying. In essence, I</span>
  <span id="freeText3466271165077877555" style="display:none">Although much of Desai's writing is lovely and lyrical, the lack of narrative drive (or to be honest, anything remotely resembling a plot) made this a bit of a drag. Others have mentioned the humor, but I found the entire thing almost relentlessly depressing, despite the quirky characters. I found the ending chapters (which includes the kidnapping of a beloved animal, something that I found both a pandering to the emotions - and ultimately heartbreaking), disturbingly unsatisfying. In essence, I feel the two other books that I've read which were shortlisted for the Booker that year (Mother's Milk and The Night Watch) might have been worthier recipients of the main prize. And it is interesting to compare the sections of this dealing with Biju's immigrant experience in America, with what happens in this year's shortlisted book 'The Year of the Runaways'.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3466271165077877555" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


